	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">YqjI transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>For quantitative DNase I footprinting , the following concentrations of oligomeric apo-YqjI were used : 1 , 2 , 5 , 10 , 15 , 20 , 25 , 30 , 35 , 40 , 45 , 50 , 55 , 60 , 70 , 80 , 90 , 100 , 120 , 140 , 160 , 180 , 200 , 250 , 300 , and 400 nM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_2">
Interestingly , YqjI is present in afﬁnity puriﬁed protein extracts only when the entire suf operon is expressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20936830" target="_blank">20936830</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_2", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>Interestingly , YqjI is present in protein extracts only when the entire suf operon is expressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20936830" target="_blank">20936830</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The YqjI band is also present in SufABCDSE negative control extracts ( data not shown ) , dem-onstrating that YqjI binds nonspeciﬁcally to the Ni2 + column .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20936830" target="_blank">20936830</a>]<br></li>
<li>The YqjI band is also present in SufABCDSE negative control extracts , and therefore may bind nonspeciﬁcally to the Ni2 + column .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20936830" target="_blank">20936830</a>]<br></li>
<li>Communication between Binding Sites Is Required for YqjI Regulation of Target Promoters within the yqjH-yqjI Intergenic Region Suning Wang , * Matthew Blahut , Yun Wu , Katherine E. Philipkosky , F. Wayne Outten Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry , University of South Carolina , Columbia , South Carolina , USA The nickel-responsive transcription factor YqjI represses its own transcription and transcription of the divergent yqjH gene , which encodes a novel ferric siderophore reductase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fur and the Novel Regulator YqjI Control Transcription of the Ferric Reductase Gene yqjH in Escherichia coli † Suning Wang , Yun Wu , and F. Wayne Outten * ent of Chemistry and Biochemistry , University of South Carolina , Columbia , South Carolina Received 7 September 2010/Accepted 7 November 2010 Departm Iron acquisition in aerobic habitats is complicated by the low solubility of ferric hydroxides .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Attempts to remove all bound metals by overnight incubation of YqjI with EDTA resulted in protein precipitation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several changes were made to the previous YqjI expression and puriﬁcation protocol to acquire better activity and higher purity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was also shown by DNA microarray experiments that YqjI expression is lower in the fnr strain , although the signiﬁcance of this result under aerobic conditions is unclear ( 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the yqjI strain carrying the pYqjI plasmid , addition of 1 mM nickel increased yqjH expression to the same high level that was observed in the complete absence of yqjI ( compare Fig. 8A to 2C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>This study shows that YqjI is the primary regulator of yqjH transcription , since deletion of yqjI leads to a 40-fold increase in yqjH basal expression while deletion of fur derepresses yqjH by only 3-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , yqjI expression in a yqjI strain lacking the YqjI repressor is increased approximately 130-fold to 4,416 111 Miller units compared to the wild-type strain ( 34 0.3 Miller units ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>For comparison , in the yqjI strain lacking the YqjI repressor , yqjH expression is increased approximately 40-fold ( from 12 Miller units for the wild-type strain to 480 35 Miller units in the mutant ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>For comparison , yqjH expression in the yqjI strain completely lacking the YqjI repressor is increased approximately 40-fold compared to that in the wild-type strain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Multiple signal inputs may be required to fully reverse YqjI repression of yqjH in vivo in the wild-type background .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>FIG 5 Effect of mutations in distal YqjI binding sites on YqjI repression of proximal promoter-lacZ fusions in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_18">
FIG 3 Effect of mutations in site I on YqjI repression of yqjH-lacZ fusions in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_18", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>FIG 6 Effect of REP element mutations on YqjI repression of yqjH-lacZ ( A ) or yqjI-lacZ ( B ) fusions in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>To test if this regulatory loop is occurring in vivo , one must uncouple expression of YqjI from its native promoter so that the addition of nickel will no longer lead to increased YqjI expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is likely that the loss of IscR repression under nickel stress ( when iron and Fe-S ho-meostasis are disrupted ) leads to increased expression of apo-YqjI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The addition of divalent metal ions , such as Ni2 , Fe2 , or Zn2 , diminishes the DNA binding afﬁnity of YqjI for these putative target sequences in vitro , possibly by interacting with YqjI via the N-terminal extension .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>We clearly observed that the DNA-binding activity of YqjI was signiﬁcantly diminished in the presence of Ni2 or Fe2 ( and mildly altered by Zn2 ) , indicating that YqjI can be regulated in vitro by multiple metals .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the in vitro nickel binding by apo-YqjI , we determined if the presence of nickel alters oligomer YqjI binding to PyqjH or PyqjI binding sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The metal-binding domain of SlyD , which is similar to the YqjI N terminus , also can bind multiple metals in vitro , but the slyD phenotype is speciﬁcally rescued by nickel addition in vivo ( 22 , 27 , 52 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>One regulatory model , suggested by the in vivo regulation , in vivo phenotype , and in vitro metal-binding studies , shows that nickel or other ligands act as a molecular switch to negatively regulate YqjI DNA-binding activity by directly binding the N-terminal SlyD-like domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although nickel can regulate YqjI DNA-binding activity in vitro , the nickel induction of the yqjH and yqjI promoters is rather mild in vivo , especially compared to the high constitutive expression observed in the yqjI strain ( Fig. 2D ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results indicate that divalent metals such as Ni2 and Fe2 have a similar negative effect on YqjI DNA-binding activity in vitro , although the observed nickel regulation parallels the in vivo nickel-speciﬁc YqjI-de-pendent regulation of the yqjH promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI repression of these target promoters is weakly responsive to elevated nickel in vivo , although YqjI DNA-binding activity is clearly altered by transition metals in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , at present we can not conclude that nickel directly binds YqjI to regulate DNA-binding activity in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI binding to nickel or iron reduces YqjI DNA-binding activity in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Divalent metals can regulate YqjI DNA-binding activity in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the observed regulation by Fur , the presence of a potential nickel-binding region within the YqjI transcriptional-regulator , and the observed regulation of yqjH and yqjI by YqjI , we tested if expression of yqjH is altered by transition metal ions in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The potential nickel-binding N terminus of YqjI and the in vivo nickel-responsive regulation of yqjH suggest that YqjI activity may be directly or indirectly regulated by divalent metals .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The in vivo YqjI-dependent nickel-responsive regulation of yqjH and the in vitro nickel binding by YqjI suggest a model in which YqjI may regulate yqjH directly in response to nickel levels in order to integrate iron and nickel homeostasis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>We also tested if excess zinc is capable of displacing nickel bound to YqjI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result indicates that YqjI also represses its own transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the autoregulation of yqjI indicates that increase nickel levels block YqjI repression of yqjI transcription , thereby causing levels of the YqjI apoprotein to increase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result indicates that nickel addition is able to completely block YqjI repression of yqjH so long as YqjI protein levels are not allowed to increase due to the YqjI auto-regulatory circuit ( Fig. 8B ) or differential regulation of YqjI by other factors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together these results suggest a model where transcription repression by apo-YqjI is abolished when nickel binds to YqjI , leading to increased expression from YqjI-regulated target promoters ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result further indicates that YqjI repression of target promoters is somehow responsive to elevated nickel in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>We utilized mutagenesis and DNase I footprinting to characterize YqjI regulation of the yqjH-yqjI intergenic region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Puriﬁed YqjI binds inverted repeat target sequences within the yqjH and yqjI promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI binds to target sequences in the yqjH-yqjI intergenic region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nickel induction of yqjH can then be measured without the added complication of YqjI autoregulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the altered regulation in the rcnA strain , it seems likely that YqjI , which provides nickel-responsive regulation of yqjH , responds to the same intracellular pool of nickel transported by RcnA ( 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results suggest that the YqjI protein controls expression of yqjH to help maintain iron homeostasis under conditions ( such as elevated cellular nickel levels ) that disrupt iron metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results suggest that YqjI may regulate yqjH and other target genes to protect iron homeostasis from disruption by environmental stresses , such as elevated intracellular nickel levels .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nickel-dependent regulation of yqjH by YqjI in minimal medium occurs beginning at nickel concentrations above 100 nM , with maximum induction between 500 nM and 1 M .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the in vivo results show that YqjI regulates yqjH speciﬁcally ( although somewhat weakly ) in response to nickel .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together , our results indicate that YqjI is re quired for nickel-dependent regulation of yqjH , while Fur is required for iron - and cobalt-dependent regulation of yqjH .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI and Fur regulate yqjH .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together , these results conﬁrm that both Fur and YqjI repress transcription of yqjH .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The nickel-dependent regulation of yqjH and yqjI by YqjI is physiologically consistent with the nickel homeostasis systems in E. coli that are regulated by the NikR and RcnR transcription factors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI autoregulation may lead to dampening of yqjH nickel induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI represses yqjH transcription and is a nickel-binding protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Role of YqjI in yqjH nickel regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Protein precipitation began to occur when the molar ratio of Ni2 to YqjI monomers increased to above 4:1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>If cells were grown in LB supplemented with 500 M nickel chloride , the Ni2 / YqjI ratio increased to 1.1 for the monomer form and 1.6 for the oligomer form of YqjI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>To avoid chelation of Ni2 off the HisTrap column by apo-YqjI , - ME was excluded in both the HisTrap binding buffer and elution buffer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION Binding of oligomeric apo-YqjI to its operator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">YqjI protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>Residues 57 to 207 of YqjI are similar to those of the PadR-family of winged-helix-turn-helix ( wHTH ) transcription factors ( InterPro accession no .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>A model three-dimensional structure of YqjI was calculated using the crystal structure of AphA , a PadR homologue from V. chol-erae , as a template ( 16 , 44 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since YqjI has a theoretical molecular weight of 23,401 , the ﬁrst heparin peak likely contained predominantly the monomer form of YqjI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ﬁrst YqjI elution peak contained monomeric YqjI , while the second elution peak contained an oligomeric form of YqjI that is likely tetrameric or a higher quaternary structure ( as subsequently determined by gel ﬁltration chromatography ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fractions containing oligomer and monomer forms of YqjI were pooled separately for further puriﬁcation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>The last two elution peaks were found by SDS-PAGE to contain YqjI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>For protein metal analysis , apo-YqjI and holo-YqjI were diluted to 0.5 to 1.0 mg/ml in 4 ml buffer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>( B ) Diagram of the YqjI protein domain organization with predicted secondary structural elements shown for each domain ( 43 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is likely due to YqjI 's predicted afﬁnity for positively charged metalloids and the 14 histidine residues within the N-terminal third of the protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20936830" target="_blank">20936830</a>]<br></li>
<li>This spacing would place apo-YqjI operators on the same face of the DNA helix to potentially facilitate loop formation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , Ralstonia metallidurans and Pseudomonas syringae each contain a YqjI homologue with a N-terminal extension that is histidine rich but lacks the cysteine residues present in E. coli YqjI ( data not shown ) What are the key regulatory signals for YqjI in vivo ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The YqjI N terminus is also similar to residues 121 to 147 of the RcnA Ni2 / Co2 efﬂux transporter that are located on a loop between predicted transmembrane domains 3 and 4 and are part of the histidine-rich signature motif that characterizes major facilitator superfamily ( MFS ) transporters that efﬂux nickel ( Fig. 2B ) ( 46 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The comparison to AphA suggests that residues 62 to 152 of YqjI constitute a winged helix fold DNA-binding domain , while residues 153 to 206 form an oligo-merization and/or ligand-binding domain ( Fig. 2B ) ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the in vitro nickel-binding by apo-YqjI , we determined if the presence of nickel alters oligomer YqjI binding to PyqjH or PyqjI binding sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>To characterize the DNA-binding activity of YqjI , we overexpressed and puriﬁed wild-type YqjI in E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI binding to nickel or iron reduces YqjI DNA-binding activity in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Divalent metals can regulate YqjI DNA-binding activity in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The potential nickel-binding N terminus of YqjI and the in vivo nickel-responsive regulation of yqjH suggest that YqjI activity may be directly or indirectly regulated by divalent metals .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The metal-binding domain of SlyD , which is similar to the YqjI N terminus , also can bind multiple metals in vitro , but the slyD phenotype is speciﬁcally rescued by nickel addition in vivo ( 22 , 27 , 52 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>One regulatory model , suggested by the in vivo regulation , in vivo phenotype , and in vitro metal-binding studies , shows that nickel or other ligands act as a molecular switch to negatively regulate YqjI DNA-binding activity by directly binding the N-terminal SlyD-like domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N-terminal region 1 to 54 of YqjI includes a number of potential metal-binding amino acids ( 12 histidines , 7 cysteines , and 7 glutamates ) and is similar to the SlyD C-terminal metal-binding tail ( E value of less than 0.01 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The N-terminal , SlyD-like region of E. coli YqjI is conserved mainly in species closely related to E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI is a member of the PadR-family of transcriptional regulators but contains an additional N-terminal extension that is rich in potential metal-binding residues ( such as Cys , His , and Glu ) ( 7 , 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Below the diagram is an amino acid alignment of the Cys/His-rich YqjI N terminus with SlyD and RcnA Cys/His-rich regions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">YqjI evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>While this apparent molecular weight would be most consistent with a hexamer of YqjI , most PadR family members form dimer or tetramer species .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on YqjI similarity to other PadR family members , we used the theoretical molecular weight of the YqjI tetramer for all molar calculations but refer to this complex as an YqjI oligomer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI is a member of the PadR family of transcriptional regulators but contains an additional N-terminal extension that is rich in potential metal-binding residues ( such as Cys , His , and Glu ) ( 7 , 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Residues 57 to 207 of YqjI are similar to those of the PadR family of winged helix-turn-helix ( wHTH ) transcription factors ( InterPro accession no .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>These studies establish that the PadR family member YqjI represses the transcription of yqjH and yqjI in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_RP" for="_4"><font size="5px">Processes regulated by YqjI</font></label>
				<input id="_4" type="checkbox">
				<div class="RP"><br><ul><li>The bands in the induced sample were identiﬁed by in-gel proteolysis and MALDI-TOF/TOF as SufE ( monomer ) , YqjI , SufE ( dimer ) , SufS , TufA ( translation-elongation factor Tu ) , TnaA ( tryptophanase ) , and SufB ( Supporting Information Table S3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20936830" target="_blank">20936830</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since YqjI was seen to repress its own expression ( Fig. 2D ) , we also tested to see if nickel addition alters expression of yqjI in vivo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results suggest that the YqjI protein controls expression of yqjH to help maintain iron-homeostasis under conditions ( such as elevated cellular nickel levels ) that disrupt iron metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>In a previous study , we discovered that the predicted transcription factor YqjI from Escherichia coli is a nickel-responsive transcriptional repressor that cross-regulates an iron-homeostasis gene in response to cellular nickel levels ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fur and the novel regulator YqjI control transcription of the ferric reductase gene yqjH in Escherichia coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_SIT" for="_5"><font size="5px">YqjI binding site</font></label>
				<input id="_5" type="checkbox">
				<div class="SIT"><br><ul><li>Mutagenesis of in vivo gene reporter constructs revealed that the two YqjI binding sites , while separated by nearly 200 bp , appear to communicate in order to provide full YqjI-dependent regulation at the two target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regions of the intergenic sequence protected from DNase I cleavage by apo-YqjI are indicated in black boxes ( see the text and Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequence of site I mapped by DNase I footprinting overlaps most of the palindrome identiﬁed previously , indicating this region is the binding site for apo-YqjI ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both monomer and oligomer forms of apo-YqjI were incubated with ﬂuorescent oligonucleotides matching the inverted-repeat sequences , and the change in ﬂuorescence anisotropy ( FA ) was measured ( Fig. 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Underlined nucleotide sequences below each panel indicate the apo-YqjI binding sites at each promoter and are speciﬁc for the noncoding strand .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>5 - ﬂuorescein-labeled single-stranded DNA oligos , corresponding to the predicted YqjI binding sites ( PyqjH and PyqjI ) , the predicted Fur binding site ( Pfur ) , or a randomly selected sequence ( random ) in the yqjH-yqjI promoter region , were obtained from Fisher Scientiﬁc .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>The simplest model to explain these results is that site I and site II can communicate via bending of the yqjH-yqjI intergenic region such that apo-YqjI bound at each promoter interacts to form a promoter-bridged complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the minimal palindromic sequences identiﬁed previously are quite similar , YqjI binding at the yqjI promoter resulted in an extended DNase I footprint in comparison to the footprint at the yqjH promoter ( Fig. 1 and 2B ) ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro ﬂuorescence anisotropy assays using oligonucleo-tides containing the palindromic sequences showed that apo-YqjI oligomer binds these two sequences with 69 nM afﬁnity for the yqjH site and 48 nM afﬁnity for the yqjI site ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since both the yqjH and yqjI promoters are repressed by YqjI , we tested if these inverted-repeats act as binding sites for YqjI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Puriﬁed YqjI binds inverted-repeat target sequences within the yqjH and yqjI promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the apo-YqjI oligomer binds PyqjH and PyqjI , these inverted-repeat sequences are strong candidates for the apo-YqjI binding sites within the yqjH and yqjI promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
<li>In conclusion , here we deﬁne the apo-YqjI binding sites within the yqjH-yqjI intergenic region and demonstrate that apo-YqjI binding is not equivalent at each operator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , mutagenesis of the repetitive extragenic palindromic ( REP ) elements within the yqjH-yqjI intergenic region shows that these sequences are not required for YqjI regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24982304" target="_blank">24982304</a>]<br></li>
<li>YqjI binds to target sequences in the yqjH-yqjI intergenic region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21097627" target="_blank">21097627</a>]<br></li>
				</ul></div><br>
